    "narrative": "The Zurich Zebras enter today\u2019s slate with a clear focus on exploiting favorable RHP matchups, headlined by our elite speed-threats. **Trea Turner** (79.76) and **Kyle Schwarber** (78.40) represent our strongest plays of the day against Martin P\u00e9rez; both benefit from a massive +19% SP skill advantage and premium batting order spots. **Pete Crow-Armstrong** (74.17) is an intriguing high-upside start today\u2014despite batting 8th, his 14% boost from dynamic platoon indicators and elite sprint speed metrics make him a priority play against Senga, as the Zebras prioritize his stolen base potential over a higher lineup position. Similarly, **Hyeseong Kim** (70.52) earns a strong start thanks to a combined +31% lift from park and SP skill factors, outweighing the minor penalty incurred by hitting 8th.\n\nOur most difficult bench decision involved **Josh Smith** (39.34), who narrowly missed the starting cut by falling just below our 40.0 floor. While **Josh Smith** received a significant +14% platoon boost, the daunting matchup against Logan Gilbert\u2014whose 2.86 xERA is the toughest on our board\u2014rendered him a liability today. We prefer to conserve our games-played cap rather than force a start against an elite arm. Elsewhere, we remain in a holding pattern with **Christian Yelich**, who remains on the IL, and **Zac Veen**, currently rostered in the minors. Owners should keep a close eye on **Dillon Dingler** (55.25); while he holds a strong score, his effectiveness is tied heavily to the dynamic platoon edge, and any lineup shift moving him away from the #4 spot could diminish his value. We have avoided exposure to the bottom of the order for **Gary Sanchez** (48.86) and **Kazuma Okamoto** (47.69) where possible, but given the current depth chart, they provide the necessary stability to bridge the gap between our high-ceiling leadoff hitters and our elite outfielders like **Yordan Alvarez** (68.39).",
